We must first decide which transactions “build” your liabilities balance. In our case the only “initial” entries (those with type “Initial20231231001”) are for cash deposit, bank deposit and fixed assets. These are all asset‐type items. (No “initial” liability entry is given.) Therefore the liabilities balance at the beginning (“Total Liabilities Initial Value”) is zero.

Then we scan the “Purchase…” transactions. (Usually purchases are entered and, when the status is “Unpaid” and the payment method is “Account Payable”, the amount is added to your balance‐sheet “liabilities” – that is, amounts you owe.) In the provided data the following Purchase rows have “Unpaid” as their “payment/receipt_status” and their “payment_method” is “Account Payable”: 

1. Purchase20231231001: amount 72,100.0  
2. Purchase20231231006: amount 1,380,000.0

Now, add these in sequence:
• 72,100.0  
  + 1,380,000.0 = 1,452,100.0  
  + 244,500.0 = 1,696,600.0  
  + 16,650.0 = 1,713,250.0

  + 400,320.0 = 3,546,220.0  
  + 616,320.0 = 4,162,540.0  
  + 852,480.0 = 5,015,020.0

Thus, after all transactions the liabilities “accumulated” through unpaid purchases sum to 5,015,020.0.

So the final balance sheet “liabilities” (that is, the Total Liabilities End Value) equals 5,015,020.00.
